60-Second Summary

> Hashing is used to verify integrity and securely store passwords by converting data into a fixed-length, one-way output. Algorithms like SHA-1 and MD5 were widely used historically but are now considered weak because collision attacks have become practical. Rainbow tables are precomputed databases that help attackers recover passwords from hashes, which is why modern systems use salting and stronger hashing approaches. The key lesson is that cryptographic controls must evolve over time as computing power and attack techniques improve.
